The body was discovered inside a car at Good Hope Hospital, Sutton Coldfield on Friday (April 22). A 43-year-old man from Tamworth was arrested last night on suspicion of murder and remains in custody. Police said the cause of death was currently being treated as unexplained and a post mortem examination will take place soon, while the car has been removed for forensic examination. His family have been informed of his death. A West Midlands Police spokesman said: "Our investigation into the death of a 56-year-old man from Kingstanding, Birmingham continues. "His body was found in a car at Good Hope Hospital in Sutton Coldfield on Friday. His family have been told the sad news. "A post mortem examination will take place as soon as possible. This will help us to understand what caused the man’s unexplained death. The vehicle was parked in a car park near the entrance to the hospital's accident and emergency department. Police were called following the discovery on Friday at around 4.50pm. The hospital remained open to the public, but parts were cordoned off with forensic officers seen at the scene. The spokesman added: "A 43-year-old man from Tamworth was arrested yesterday evening in Birmingham on suspicion of murder. He remains in custody. "The car has been removed for more detailed forensic examination and the area of the car park we closed off reopened. "Anyone who has any information which may help police should speak to officers at the hospital or message police via Live Chat on their website west-midlands.police.uk quoting reference number 2955-220422."